Date: Wed, 27 Sep 2000 08:51:43 +0800
From: Dr Muruga Vadivale <cyberdoc@maxis.net.my>
Source: Jerusalem Post, story filed 27 Sep 2000 [edited
<http://www.jpost.com/Editions/2000/09/27/News/News.12913.html>

Rain Could Worsen West Nile Virus Fever Outbreak
------------------------------------------------
HAIFA: Forecasts for rain in the coming days have raised concern of a
possible new wave of West Nile fever, after 2 more people died yesterday
from the disease, bringing the total number of fatalities to 19.
Health Ministry Director-General Shuki Shemer warned yesterday that
accumulation of water on the ground while the weather remains relatively
warm could increase the mosquito population. Most experts agree that
stagnant water and warm conditions are the ideal breeding conditions for
mosquitoes which are as yet the sole known carriers of the disease.
In a Knesset address, he emphasized that the outbreak was brought under
control in New York by insecticides. By spraying the water sources where
mosquitoes are nesting, the problem can be overcome here, Milo added. Light
rain is forecast in the North today, spreading to central districts
tomorrow. The rain in both regions tomorrow is expected to be sporadic but
possibly heavy in places, and may even be accompanied by some isolated
thunderstorms. The rain, which would normally be welcomed after the long hot
summer and in light of the water crisis, is expected to end Friday. It will
be cooler than usual, with a gradual rise in temperatures beginning
Saturday. That is what worries health experts, in light of the spread of
West Nile fever by mosquitoes in the summer.
However, some experts believe the methods used to deal with the mosquito
menace are inappropriate. Dr. Uri Marinov, former director-general of the
Environment Ministry, said the use of chemical insecticides and pesticides
in most developed countries was proving ineffectual. Mutations had occurred
which were immune to the various sprays and new methods had to be developed,
including the use of biological agents to destroy mosquitoes. Furthermore,
Marinov told Israel Radio that blanket spraying in urban area is less
effective than tackling the problem at its source in the stagnant waters
where the mosquitoes breed and live. He said farmers have developed
biological agents to erase the threat by attacking the larvae of the
developing insects. This is the best long-term solution and should also be
adopted in urban areas where there are pools of sewage or standing
water.
[Byline: David Rudge; Nina Gilbert contributed to this report
--
