Date: Tue, 26 Sep 2000 13:17:09 GMT-3
From ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Jerusalem Post, filed 25 Sep 2000 [edited
<http://www.jpost.com/Editions/2000/09/25/News/News.12825.html>

West Nile Virus and Ticks
-------------------------
A second elderly resident of Kibbutz Kabri died today 25 Sep 2000) of West
Nile Fever. [Previously} at Kabri, there was shock, alarm and confusion at
the weekend, following the death of one of the settlement's founders and the
hospitalization of three other members - all due to West Nile virus
infection. What was perplexing for kibbutz members is the fact that they had
treated mosquito breeding sites and also resorted to "fogging" the area when
the first case of the disease was diagnosed. "We didn't have a mosquito
problem," said one member. "And we don't know what has caused the outbreak.
"Neither do health ministry officials. "There is not always a direct link
between the appearance of the disease and the presence of mosquitoes," says
Health Ministry Deputy Director-General Dr. Boaz Lev. "Kabri is an example
of that."It's possible that mosquitoes from a neighboring settlement
infected people. Or there was some subtle change in the ecological balance
that we don't yet understand."Kibbutz Kabri does have an abundance of
pigeons, which are now being tested for the disease. If the birds prove to
be infected, it could raise another disturbing possibility: that the virus
was not transmitted by mosquitoes at all, but by ticks.
Although mosquitoes are commonly thought to be the only living things that
can infect people with the virus, the United States Center for Disease
Control (CDC) suggests another scenario: "In general, only infected
mosquitoes transmit West Nile virus. However, ticks may transmit West Nile
virus between birds and, possibly, from infected birds to people," according
to the Center's Division of Epidemiology and Immunization web site.
"Although no West Nile virus was isolated from ticks in the United States
during the 1999 outbreak, ticks may prove to be vectors of West Nile Virus
transmission in the future," reports the CDC, which then sounds this
warning: " It is important to realize that infected ticks cannot be killed
by aerial insecticide spraying as mosquitoes can, and that infected ticks,
therefore, may prove to be a very important vector in the possible future
spread of West Nile virus in the United States."
Lev says, in response, that "to the best of my knowledge, ticks do not
transmit the virus."
[Byline Leora Eren Frucht
